	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Reviews of the production, trade and income consequences of EU direct aid payments</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 August 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Two papers have been published reviewing the EU’s direct aid payments system. An academic paper from Humboldt University reviews the production and trade effects of EU direct aid payments, while the EC evaluation is more narrowly focused on the effects of EU direct aid payments on farmers’ incomes.</p><p>The Humboldt University paper seeks to review the common assertion that EU direct aid payments are production- and trade-neutral. It maintains that ‘the system of direct aid payments in its present form has effects which are analogous to a subsidization of agricultural land.’ It suggests that by reducing risks for producer, direct aid payments stimulate production and investment and thereby ‘act to increase production and trade’.</p><p>The paper further maintains that ‘commodities for which the European Union is a net exporter are sold below cost, for extended periods of time and in substantial quantities.’ It concludes that ‘the EU system of decoupled payments to farmers, thus, acts to inflict injury to third countries’, and suggests that in some sectors such as wheat this constitutes ‘dumping’ (i.e. EU goods are being sold on foreign markets below the cost of production).</p><p>On this basis, the paper concludes that direct aid payments should be classified as ‘amber box’ payments in the WTO categorisation, given their production and trade effects (including reducing world market prices). Overall the analysis concludes that ‘an abolishment of the CAP subsidy system in the EU would have positive impacts on agricultural producer prices and trade in third countries.’ It maintains that ‘the subsidies paid under the present system … [violate] WTO trade regulations on markets in which the European Union is an exporter.’ This is held to be particularly the case in the wheat sector.</p><p>The EC evaluation, which focuses exclusively on the income effects of direct aid payments, has a number of conclusions which underline the basic risk-reduction function of direct aid payments that underpins the case made in the Humboldt University paper. It concludes, among other things, that direct aid payments ‘contributed to enhancing the income of farmers’, and contributed to stabilising the income of farmers. It found that direct aid payments have been ‘crucial in ensuring the economic viability of farms, in particular those specialising in field crops, grazing livestock (beef, sheep and goats), mixed farming and, partly, in the milk sector’.</p><p>Given the income-related objectives of CAP policy measures, the evaluation called for an extension of direct payment arrangements to the horticulture and permanent-crops sectors (with the exception of wine), since these sectors suffer from ‘the lowest farm income levels per labour unit’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Humboldt University of Berlin, ‘Decoupled payments to EU farmers, production and trade: An economic analysis for Germany’, paper by H. von Witzke, S. Noleppa and G. Schwarz, <i>Working Paper 90</i>, downloadable from agripol.de entry for 29 March 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.agripol.de/home.htm" target="_self">http://www.agripol.de/home.htm</a> <br/>
EC, ‘Evaluation of income effects of direct support’, executive summary of an evaluation of the income effects of EU direct aid payments, May 2011<br/>

<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/eval/reports/income/exec_sum_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/eval/reports/income/exec_sum_en.pdf</a><br/>
EC, ‘Evaluation of income effects of direct support’, full report of an evaluation of the income effects of EU direct aid payments, May 2011<br/>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/eval/reports/income/fulltext_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/eval/reports/income/fulltext_en.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The Humboldt University analysis suggests, despite the EC claims to the contrary, that EU direct aid payments affect production and trade outcomes and that this causes harm to third-country producers. The analysis however, by looking at the global level, provides little insight into the trade effects of EU direct aid payment arrangements on individual ACP economies. Given the scale of most ACP economies, evenly relatively minor EU export volumes could have a disproportionate effect on local markets.</p><p>Given the centrality of the single-payment scheme to the process of CAP reform, it is unlikely that the EU could contemplate reclassifying the single-payment scheme into the ‘amber box’, based on its production and trade consequences. Any such reclassification would potentially leave the single-payment scheme subject to expenditure reductions under WTO rules.</p><p>Against this background, ACP governments may wish to review the policy tools which they would like to retain the right to use, in order to deal with any unforeseen adverse trade consequences which might arise from the deployment of EU direct aid payments. This is an important issue, since while the EU is likely to reduce the use of internationally recognised trade-distorting tools (e.g. export subsidies) as part of its 2013 round of CAP reforms, it is likely to extend the use of the single-payment scheme, the principal instrument for the deployment of direct aid payments.</p>
		</div>
		
